🛠️ The Fix: Use Chrome's Flag Override
You do not need to buy a domain name or set up complicated SSL certificates to bypass this. Google Chrome has a hidden developer feature built exactly for this situation, letting you tell your phone to treat your cloud server's IP as a secure zone.

Follow these quick steps on your phone:

1. Open flags in mobile Chrome
Open the Chrome application on your mobile device, type this address into your URL text bar, and hit enter:

Plaintext
chrome://flags
2. Search for unsecure origins
In the search bar at the top of the internal page that appears, type:

Plaintext
unsafely-treat-insecure-origin-as-secure
3. Enable and add your server IP
Change the dropdown box value from Disabled to Enabled.

In the text box right below it, paste your exact server link structure:

Plaintext
http://34.201.143.168
4. Relaunch your browser
Click the blue Relaunch button that pops up at the bottom of your phone screen. This restarts the Chrome engine with your new developer rules active.

🏁 Test the Feed
Now, go back to your transmitter page on your phone:

Plaintext
http://34.201.143.168/camera-stream
Your phone will pop up an explicit permission message asking for Camera Access. Click Allow, and your live video lens feed will pop right up onto your screen and stream straight to your desktop dashboard!

